“Good enough for me” is almost a meta-joke itself. Comedy rarely has a formal proof. If the room laughs, the hypothesis survived contact with reality.

It reminds me of a kind of empirical rule:

Comedy = prediction → surprise → coherence.

If the audience can’t predict it, they’re just confused.
If they predict it perfectly, they’re bored.
If they predict almost the wrong thing and then instantly reconstruct the intended meaning—that’s often where the laugh lives.

So in your framing, it’s less “humor follows rules” and more:

Humor follows patterns that exploit the rules of human prediction.

That’s why timing matters. Delivery matters. Pauses matter. They’re all ways of shaping the audience’s internal trajectory before the reveal.

As comedians often discover, you don’t really know whether a joke works until it collides with an audience. That’s one of the few domains where “I’m betting it works” is a perfectly reasonable experimental method.